      <h2>Assembly</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Always make sure the power tool is unplugged during assembly.</strong>
      </div>

      <h3>Shaft and Sheath Adjustment</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p05_00.jpg" alt="Diagram showing proper shaft extension of 3/4 inch beyond sheath" />
        <figcaption>Shaft must extend 3/4&Prime; (19 mm) beyond the sheath</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the handpiece by pulling it off the shaft with a firm grip (tool must be unplugged).</li>
        <li>Place the unit on a flat surface with shaft and sheath extended straight.</li>
        <li>Loosen the set screw on the motor connector.</li>
        <li>Adjust the exposed tip of the flexible shaft so it extends 3/4&Prime; (19 mm) beyond the sheath by moving the sheath in or out of the motor connector.</li>
        <li>Retighten the set screw in the motor connector.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Important:</strong> The shaft and sheath should be checked and adjusted even if you received them already assembled and attached to the motor.
      </div>

      <h3>Re-attaching the Handpiece</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p05_04.jpg" alt="Key tip end of shaft showing keyway alignment" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p05_05.jpg" alt="Metal sheath tip connection point" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Hold the black metal outer sheath tip facing upward.</li>
        <li>Turn on the motor to about half speed, then turn it off.</li>
        <li>While the inner key tip is still rotating, grip the handpiece and push it onto the sheath tip with one firm motion until it snaps into place.</li>
        <li>To verify: insert and tighten an accessory, turn the control to low speed, and observe that the accessory rotates smoothly.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Connecting Foot Speed Control</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p06_01.jpg" alt="Diagram showing foot speed control wiring connections with socket connector and power outlet plug" />
        <figcaption>Foot control connection: motor plug to socket connector, foot control plug to wall outlet</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Insert the shielded 3-prong plug on the motor power cord into the socket connector on the shorter power cord of the foot control.</li>
        <li>With the foot control in the &ldquo;off&rdquo; position (not depressed), plug the 3-prong plug on the longer cord into a proper 3-wire power outlet.</li>
        <li>Hold the handpiece securely before engaging the foot pedal.</li>
        <li>Press down with a light touch, start slowly, and gradually increase speed.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Connecting Table-Top Dial Speed Control (EMX)</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p06_02.jpg" alt="Diagram of EMX dial speed control showing fuse compartment location" />
        <figcaption>EMX dial control with fuse compartment</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Plug the shielded 3-prong power cord from the motor into the short cord on the dial control.</li>
        <li>With the motor fwd/off/rev switch in &ldquo;off&rdquo; and the dial control also in &ldquo;off,&rdquo; connect the detachable power cord to the dial control and into a proper 3-wire outlet.</li>
        <li>Hold the handpiece, set the motor switch to the desired &ldquo;on&rdquo; position, and gradually increase speed.</li>
        <li>If the motor is overloaded, the fuse may blow. The fuse is located below the detachable power cord receptacle.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Hanging Motor Installation</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p06_03.jpg" alt="Motor hanging installation showing safety clip and proper mounting height" />
        <figcaption>Hang motor 25&ndash;40&Prime; above work surface with safety clip</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>Hang the motor 25&ndash;40&Prime; above the work surface, to the right if right-handed or to the left if left-handed. Use a safety clip or hook to prevent the motor from jumping or twisting off at startup. If using an open hook, secure the motor with wire or tape.</p>

