      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Always wear proper eye and face protection when operating.</strong> Flying debris, chips, or sparks can cause serious eye or face injuries.
      </div>

      <h3>General Guidelines</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p12_00.jpg" alt="Illustration showing proper operating position and minimum shaft bend radius" />
        <figcaption>Proper operation: maintain at least a 4&Prime; bend radius on the flexible shaft</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li>Let the speed of the tool do the work. Avoid forcing or applying excessive pressure.</li>
        <li>Slower speeds are better for rough, heavy work or precise/delicate operations. Higher speeds for buffing, cutting, and polishing.</li>
        <li>Practice on scrap material to determine the best accessories and speeds for your application.</li>
        <li>The motor may operate vertically or horizontally but should not be enclosed or confined (needs air circulation).</li>
        <li>The motor may develop high operating temperatures (up to 100&deg;F + ambient) after prolonged use &mdash; this is normal and will not harm the motor.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Do not bend the shaft at tight angles.</strong> Maintain at least a 4&Prime; bend radius. Sharp bends cause excessive friction, heat, and accelerated wear at the bend points.
      </div>

      <h3>Speed and Accessory Selection</h3>
      <p>The TX Series motor has a maximum speed of 15,000 RPM. Always use accessories rated for 15,000 RPM or higher.</p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Accessory Type</th><th>Applications</th><th>Speed Notes</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Abrasive points &amp; wheels</td><td>Grinding, smoothing on steel, glass, porcelain</td><td>Finer grits at higher speeds; coarser grits at lower speeds</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Carbide burs / Typhoon burs</td><td>Wood, plastic, tough alloys</td><td>Medium speeds for stock removal; higher for finishing</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cut-off wheels</td><td>Cutting, grooving, trimming metal/wood/ceramics</td><td>Follow manufacturer RPM rating</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sanding drums &amp; bands</td><td>Rust removal, smoothing, sanding</td><td>Medium speeds for coarser grits; higher for finishing</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cotton/felt bobs &amp; buffs</td><td>Buffing and polishing with compounds</td><td>High speeds for cutting/buffing; medium for polishing</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Brushes</td><td>Deburring, cleaning, edge blending</td><td>High speeds for cleaning; medium for hard-to-reach areas</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Drills</td><td>Drilling wood, metals, bone, ceramics</td><td>Follow manufacturer RPM rating</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Always unplug the power tool before performing any maintenance.</strong>
      </div>

      <h3>Routine Motor Cleaning</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p13_00.jpg" alt="Motor housing showing air inlet and outlet slots that need cleaning" />
        <figcaption>Motor air circulation slots require regular cleaning</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>The motor has permanently lubricated ball bearings and does not require additional lubrication. However, dust and conductive debris (metal filings, gold dust) can enter through the air circulation slots and cause electrical shorts.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>In high-dust environments, clean the motor every 40 hours of use.</li>
        <li>Remove motor brushes, clean and replace them, and blow air through the motor to remove debris.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Shaft Cleaning and Lubrication</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p13_01.jpg" alt="Step showing removal of handpiece from shaft" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p13_02.jpg" alt="Step showing loosening set screw on motor connector" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p13_03.jpg" alt="Step showing sliding outer sheath off to expose inner shaft" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the handpiece.</li>
        <li>Loosen the set screw on the motor connector.</li>
        <li>Slide the outer sheath out of the motor connector and wipe the inner shaft clean.</li>
        <li>Apply a very light coating of Foredom flex shaft grease (MS10006) or quality white lubricating grease, starting at the top and working downward to about 3&Prime; from the handpiece end. Use less near the handpiece end to prevent seepage.</li>
        <li>Replace and adjust the sheath so the key tip extends 3/4&Prime; from the sheath. Retighten the set screw.</li>
        <li>Clean the outside of the sheath.</li>
        <li>Hang and run the motor for about 10 minutes before attaching the handpiece to allow grease to spread and drain off. Wipe any excess at the tip end.</li>
        <li>Re-attach the handpiece.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Lubrication schedule:</strong> Wipe and re-lubricate the shaft every 40 hours of use. Every 200 hours, thoroughly clean the shaft with solvent before re-lubricating.
      </div>

      <h3>Replacing Motor Brushes</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p14_00.jpg" alt="New motor brush compared to worn brush showing replacement threshold" />
        <figcaption>New brush (3/4&Prime;) vs. brush needing replacement (1/4&Prime;)</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect the motor power cord.</li>
        <li>Unscrew the brush caps.</li>
        <li>Remove worn brushes (replace when worn to 1/4&Prime; / 6 mm; new brushes are 3/4&Prime; / 19 mm).</li>
        <li>Insert new motor brushes and screw the brush caps back on.</li>
        <li>Always replace both brushes, even if one is less worn than the other.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Replacing Worn Shafts and Sheaths</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p14_02.jpg" alt="Motor connector removal with wrench" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/foredom-tx/p14_03.jpg" alt="Flexible shaft motor coupling and set screw" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Expose the inner shaft (remove handpiece, loosen set screw, slide sheath out).</li>
        <li>Remove the motor connector with a 1&Prime; wrench &mdash; the motor connector has a <strong>left-hand thread</strong> (turn clockwise to remove).</li>
        <li>Loosen the set screw on the flexible shaft motor coupling and slide the shaft off the motor shaft.</li>
        <li>Install the new shaft: slide coupling onto motor shaft and tighten set screw onto the flat.</li>
        <li>Grease the new shaft before putting on the sheath.</li>
        <li>Slide the sheath over the shaft with the plain fitting toward the motor. The grooved fitting goes toward the handpiece.</li>
        <li>Adjust the shaft extension to 3/4&Prime; and tighten the sheath set screw.</li>
      </ol>

